by Brigadier J. C. Haydon, D.S.O., O.B.E., Commanding Spectral Service Brigade.

13th March, 1941.

Objects of the operation.

x. (a) The Military objects of the operation were to destroy the facilities for producing herring and cod oil in the Ports of Stamsund, Hennmgsvaer, Svolvaer and Brettesnes, all of which are situated in the Lofoten Islands; to arrest local supporters of the Quisling party; to capture any enemy personnel found in the ports, and to enlist recruits for the Free Nor- wegiati Forces. .

(6) The Naval objective at the ports was the destruction or capture of enemy ships and of Norwegian vessels found to be working for the Germans.

Concentration of the force and preparatory work.

4. Operational Headquarters Special Service Brigade, Nos. 3 and 4 Commandos, the Royal Engineers detachment and the Norwegian troops embarked at Gourock in H.M.S. QUEEN EMMA and H.M.S. PRINCESS BEATRIX during the afternoon of Friday, 21st February, 1941, and left for Scapa Flow on the evening of that day. .

Scapa was reached at 1430 hours on the 2and February and the ships were anchored between HAMS. NELSON and H.M.S KING GEORGE

The troops remained at Scapa until the force sailed for the Lofoten Islands at ooor hours on Saturday, rst March, 1941 Thus, there in- tervened a period of almost a week during which all the final arrangements, plans and orders could be prepared, published and ex- plained and during which those who were to operate together during the operation could meet and get to know one another.:

There can be no doubt whatsoever regarding the essential nature of this comparatively short time of preparation. . ——

Though the nature of the raid precluded meticulous rehearsals of the tasks allotted to each troop or detachment, the week at Scapa was invaluable from the military point of view, in that 1t gave both officers and men time to accustom themselves to the ships from which they were to work; to get to know the officers and crews of the landing craft which were to take them inshore, and, in general, to make the personal contacts which are so essential a pre- liminary to an enterprise of this kind.

5. So far as the Naval and Military Com- manders were concerned, the period at Scapa was filled by a series of conferences, at which all details and difficulties were examined and solutions reached. 1

Several points of major importance emerged during these meetings. The first concerned the problem of supporting fire from the destroyers.

Captain C. Caslon, R.N., the Senior Naval Officer, having studied the charts of the area of operations, reached the conclusion that, owing to navigational difficulties, the escorting des- troyers would not be able to lie closer than ap- proximately I mile from each port.
